# kube-prod-contexts.example
#
# Substring patterns marking a kube context as "production / dangerous". When the
# resolved current-context matches ANY pattern below, even read commands are
# blocked unless an explicit --context (helm: --kube-context) is given.
#
# One pattern per line; '#' starts a comment. Matching is plain substring.
#
# Resolution order used by kube-context-guard.py (first existing file wins):
#   1. $OPENCODE_KUBE_GUARD_PROD_FILE
#   2. ~/.claude/.kube-prod-contexts   (your private file — keep cluster ARNs/account IDs THERE, not here)
#   3. this bundled example
#   4. built-in defaults: prod, production, prd
#
# Do NOT commit real cluster names / AWS account IDs to a shared repo. Put those
# in your private ~/.claude/.kube-prod-contexts instead. Generic defaults only:

prod
production
prd
